---
import ComponentLayout from '@/layouts/ComponentLayout.astro'
---

<ComponentLayout name='Prose'>
	<div class='prose'>
		<h2>Prose Documentation</h2>
		<p>
			The <code>.prose</code> class is a utility wrapper designed to provide consistent and readable
			typography styles for long-form text content, such as articles, blog posts, documentation
			pages, or any content primarily composed of standard HTML text elements. It ensures a clear
			visual hierarchy and optimal vertical rhythm for improved readability without requiring specific
			classes on every individual element.
		</p>
		<p>
			It is particularly useful for content generated from a rich text editor (WYSIWYG) or
			markdown, where direct control over individual element classes might be limited.
		</p>

		<h3>Usage</h3>
		<p>
			To apply the prose styles, simply wrap your text-heavy content in a <code>
				&lt;div&gt;
			</code>
			or other block-level element with the <code>.prose</code> class.
		</p>

		<pre><code>&lt;div class="prose"&gt;
  &lt;h1&gt;Your Page Title&lt;/h1&gt;
  &lt;p&gt;This is a paragraph of content.&lt;/p&gt;
  &lt;h2&gt;A Section Heading&lt;/h2&gt;
  &lt;p&gt;Another paragraph, naturally flowing below.&lt;/p&gt;
  &lt;ul&gt;
    &lt;li&gt;List item 1&lt;/li&gt;
    &lt;li&gt;List item 2&lt;/li&gt;
  &lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;</code></pre>

		<h3>Styling Applied</h3>
		<p>
			The <code>.prose</code> class primarily manages vertical spacing (<code>
				margin-block-start
			</code>) between block-level elements within its scope, respecting a consistent rhythm
			and creating appropriate separation for headings. It uses the following logic:
		</p>

		<pre><code is:raw>.prose {
  &gt; :not(:first-child) {
    margin-block-start: 1em; /* Base vertical spacing between elements */

    &amp;:where(h1, .h1, h2, .h2, h3, .h3, h4, .h4, h5, .h5, h6, .h6) {
      margin-block-start: 1.5em; /* Increased spacing before headings */
    }
  }
}</code></pre>

		<h4>Key Features:</h4>
		<ul>
			<li>
				<strong>Smart Vertical Rhythm:</strong> Automatically applies a base
				<code>1em</code> top margin to all child elements except the very first one, preventing
				unnecessary space at the top of the prose block.
			</li>
			<li>
				<strong>Heading Hierarchy:</strong> Headings (<code>h1</code>-<code>h6</code>, and
				their corresponding <code>.h1</code>-<code>.h6</code> classes) receive an increased
				<code>1.5em</code> top margin, providing greater visual separation and emphasizing the
				start of new sections.
			</li>
			<li>
				<strong>Em-based Spacing:</strong> Spacing is defined in <code>em</code> units, meaning
				it scales relative to the <code>font-size</code> of the parent element, ensuring consistent
				proportions even if font sizes change within the content.
			</li>
			<li>
				<strong>Flexibility:</strong> Works seamlessly with any standard HTML block-level elements,
				including paragraphs, lists, blockquotes, images, and other custom components that are
				direct children of the <code>.prose</code> container.
			</li>
		</ul>

		<h3>Example of Applied Styling</h3>
		<div class='prose padding-md' style='border: 1px dashed var(--color-border);'>
			<h1>A Top-Level Heading</h1>
			<p>
				This is the first paragraph. Notice it does not have a top margin pushing it away
				from the container's top edge. This text simulates rich content, ensuring that it's
				fully responsive and accessible across various devices.
			</p>
			<h2>A Secondary Heading</h2>
			<p>
				Following the secondary heading, this paragraph begins. It has a
				<code>1em</code> margin above it, and the heading itself has a <code>1.5em</code>
				margin above it, creating a clear break from the previous content.
			</p>
			<h3>A Tertiary Heading</h3>
			<ul>
				<li>List item one.</li>
				<li>List item two.</li>
				<li>List item three.</li>
			</ul>
			<p>Another paragraph, demonstrating consistent spacing below a list.</p>
			<h4>A Fourth-Level Heading</h4>
			<p>
				Even for smaller headings, the increased `margin-block-start` helps visually
				separate sections.
			</p>
		</div>

		<h3>Best Practices</h3>
		<ul>
			<li>
				<strong>Use as a Wrapper:</strong> Always apply <code>.prose</code> as a wrapper around
				a block of content, not directly to individual elements within the content.
			</li>
			<li>
				<strong>Avoid Overlapping Styles:</strong> Be mindful of other global CSS rules or utility
				classes that might unintentionally override the spacing provided by
				<code>.prose</code> for its direct children.
			</li>
			<li>
				<strong>Semantic HTML:</strong> The effectiveness of <code>.prose</code> relies on using
				semantic HTML elements (<code>&lt;p&gt;</code>, <code>&lt;h1&gt;</code>-<code>
					&lt;h6&gt;
				</code>,
				<code>&lt;ul&gt;</code>, <code>&lt;ol&gt;</code>, <code>&lt;blockquote&gt;</code>,
				etc.) for your content structure.
			</li>
		</ul>
	</div>
</ComponentLayout>
